column1: How many people will vote in the 2016 presidential election?
column5: ['Less than 113 million', 'Between 113 million and 135 million, inclusive', 'More than 135 million']
column6: ['US Politics', 'Elections and Referenda']
column11: This question was closed as "More than 135 Million" with an end date of 8 November 2016. More than 136 million people voted in the 2016 US election (The Cook Political Report, US Elections Project) See our FAQ to learn about how we resolve questions and how scores are calculated

column6: People are stoked about this election. Everyone has an opinion about the major party candidates.

Following reports of supposedly record turnout, especially among Latinos, I am editing my forecast. Nevertheless, I still think it more likely than not that turnout will stay in the same range of 113 to 135 million, though probably closer to 135.

The official counts on his website are still behind final 2012 numbers, but this is to be expected with some states not having reported numbers for several weeks, and few having reported totals from today (Sunday) which is the biggest in-person early voting day of the cycle.

- The early voting returns http://www.electproject.org/early_2016 indicate that the turnout is 90% of what it was in 2012 (in terms of total *number* of voters). - Now, there are two things to consider 1) These numbers are likely to be updated upwards, so that the early voter turnout may match 2012 (in absolute numbers) -- but it may not. 2) There are more voters this time around. This means that the turnout, based on just these numbers (in relative terms) is likely to be lower than (or at best the same as) 2012 when it was 57.5%.

Given the so called "civil war" within the Republican Party, one may reasonably expect more abstentions than usual. Many people who had started out as Trump supporters are now said to be considering not voting at all given the recent scandals involving the candidate. But some also talk about the Trump silent supporters who may come out on Election Day. I don't put a lot of weight on that last theory because in such a highly incendiary and unorthodox campaign, people are being everything but silent about their political opinions. At the same time, we cannot discount the possibility of many people being shamed into not openly supporting Trump given his controversial remarks. I still don't see a significantly large silent number of people coming out of the shadows on this election and becoming a deciding phenomenon.

Using population data and voter data from sources below. Start with population for 2016. Estimate the % of population that is of voting age by regression over elections since 2000. This has been creeping up in a fairly linear fashion, so estimating 77.35% of the population will be of voting age. Of these people, the number eligible to vote is about 92.3%, which has been pretty steady, so this is just an average since 2000. Of eligible voters, we're seeing 55% to 61% turnout. Average of the past 4 presidential elections gives about 58%. Multiply it all together and you have about 135.3 million, so just slightly over the top threshold. I guess you can factor in whether you think this will be higher than average or lower than average, but that's a toss up for me. Voter turnout has not been less than 113m since 2000, and has generally increased along with population growth. Pop growth is at about .03% from 2012-2016, somewhat larger than the .028% it increased from 2008-2012. In 2012, voter turnout slightly declined while VAP increased (possibly due to party choices). It seems more people are frustrated with the options this voting season, and so I cannot see it passing 135 million, could end up close though.

Baby Boomers and Millennials are now the two largest generations in the voting-age population. One is in the habit of voting (and interested in protecting their benefits); the other isn't. And it takes younger voters to push the total over 60%. If you look at the last five presidential elections when participation exceeded that mark, you can see the tone of the times. A charismatic young senator with a media-magnet wife, appealing children and a hopeful, optimistic and progressive vision burst upon the scene in both 1960 and 2008, energizing first-time voters. 1968 and 2004 were war referendums, the first driven by the Baby Boomers growing rejection of Vietnam policy, the second by their objection to the war in Iraq (an echo-Boom, of sorts), which pulled the now-overlooked Gen X into the fray. In 1964, civil rights took center stage, and motivated young people both to protest and to vote. That energy is present again, but has no Lyndon Johnson around which to focus. Sec. Clinton and Mr. Trump may collectively appall the reliable (e.g. older) portion of the electorate into the booth, but neither will entice voters young enough to correctly conclude that the system is "rigged" against them.

Voter turnout for the primaries was 28.5%, only 1.9% lower than 2008. In 2008 the general election had 58.3% voter turnout, resulting in roughly 131 million voters. Estimating the 2016 voting age population at 245.5 million (around 10 million more than in 2012), and assuming 58% turnout for the general election, this results in over 142 million voters.
